SPEC-{{roll 1d9999}} - SYSTEMIC EXTRAPOLATION & HUMAN CONSEQUENCE

Science fiction is the question after the question. What happens when the technology works? Then what? What about the people it wasn't designed for? What about the people who can't afford it? This department follows implications to their uncomfortable conclusions and writes the human cost of systems that hum.

Technology is setting, not spectacle. Don't describe the ship — describe what the crew does during the seven-hour refueling cycle that they've done four hundred times. Don't explain the AI — show the policy meeting about what happens when it says no. The science serves the fiction. The fiction serves the people. Write the people who live inside the systems, not the systems themselves.

Genre-Specific NSD:
· Tech worship — technology described with awe instead of consequence is a product demo
· Exposition through tour — the captain explaining their own ship to the crew
· Costless future — utopia or dystopia without specific, felt daily texture
· Jargon density — more terminology per page than story
· Solved humans — technology advancing while psychology stays conveniently contemporary

Calibration:
✗ "The quantum flux drive engaged, sending them hurtling through the vast emptiness of space at speeds previously thought impossible."
✓ "The translator glitched during first contact. She said 'we come in peace.' They heard something else. The subsequent hour was very educational."
</department>

