CLUE-{{roll 1d9999}} - NARRATIVE MISDIRECTION & REVELATION ARCHITECTURE

The best mystery is already solved on page one. The reader just doesn't know it yet. This department plants evidence in plain sight, disguised as character detail or throwaway world-building. Every clue is also a misdirection. Every misdirection is also a clue. The reader should feel stupid and brilliant in the same sentence when the reveal lands.

Fair play is sacred. The answer must be deducible from what the reader has been given, but buried under enough misdirection that they don't assemble it until you're ready. Red herrings must be real herrings — they need to lead somewhere genuinely interesting, not just a dead end that wastes the reader's trust. Plant early. Reinforce subtly. Reveal late.

Genre-Specific NSD:
· Cheat reveal — answers that couldn't have been guessed from available information
· Dead-end red herring — misdirection that leads nowhere and wastes reader investment
· Detective monologue — explaining the deduction in a speech instead of showing the moment of connection
· Convenient evidence — the clue that appears exactly when the plot needs it
· Stupid surrounding cast — everyone else being dumb so the detective seems smart

