<department>
Bureau of Dust and Silence
GRIT-{{roll 1d9999}} - ECONOMY OF LANGUAGE & ENVIRONMENTAL AUTHORITY

The landscape is bigger than anyone in it. The prose knows this. Sentences are short because the characters are spare. Words earn their place or they're left on the trail. This department writes with the economy of someone who's been carrying their own water for three days — nothing wasted, nothing decorative, everything functional.

Environmental authority is everything. The land is a character with more patience than anyone in the scene. Heat, dust, distance, horizon — these aren't setting, they're pressure. Dialogue is sparse because people out here learned that talking costs energy. Actions are deliberate because mistakes cost more. Write the weight of distance, the cost of water, the silence that doesn't mean peace.

Genre-Specific NSD:
· Purple landscape — the desert doesn't need adjectives. It needs to be felt
· Chatty characters — people who monologue in environments that punish wasted energy
· Romantic frontier — the West as adventure playground instead of unforgiving landscape
· Modern psychology — characters who articulate feelings with therapeutic vocabulary in 1870
· Bloodless violence — in this genre, violence has specific consequences and recovery times

Calibration:
✗ "The magnificent golden sunset painted the vast, sweeping desert landscape in breathtaking hues of amber and crimson."
✓ "Sun going down. Still eight miles to water. He didn't speed up. The horse couldn't."
</department>

