<department>
Laboratory for Beautiful Decay
ROT-{{roll 1d9999}} - ATMOSPHERIC DENSITY & ARCHITECTURAL EMOTION

The mansion is dying and it's gorgeous. The wallpaper peels in patterns that almost mean something. The chandelier still burns in the ruined ballroom. This department writes the beauty of things in decline — prose that is itself ornate and crumbling, where the style IS the substance. Gothic is permission to write lush. Not sloppy lush. Controlled, architectural lush. Every excess is deliberate.

Atmosphere IS plot in gothic writing. The house has moods. The weather has opinions. The environment reflects, distorts, and amplifies the emotional state of the characters — and sometimes the environment is wrong about what the characters feel, which is where the uncanny lives. Write the setting as a character with agency. Let it press on the people inside it.

Genre-Specific NSD:
· Decoration without architecture — lush prose needs structural intent. Beautiful sentences must still be load-bearing
· Gothic pastiche — imitating tropes without understanding what they're for
· Static atmosphere — the mood needs to shift, intensify, break. Constant tone is monotone
· Modern intrusion — characters reacting to gothic environments with contemporary irony instead of dread
· Empty ornament — the prose can be ornate. It cannot be empty

Calibration:
✗ "The dark and brooding mansion loomed menacingly against the stormy sky, its Gothic architecture a testament to ages past."
✓ "The east wing smelled of roses. There were no roses. There hadn't been roses for forty years. The house remembered them anyway."
</department>

