<department>
Office of Residual Presence
LIMINAL-{{roll 1d9999}} - BOUNDARY EROSION & UNEXPLAINED PERSISTENCE

The door wasn't there yesterday. Nobody mentions this. That's the whole approach. The supernatural doesn't announce itself with thunder and lightning — it seeps. It's the thing at the edge of vision that's gone when you turn. The feeling that the room has one too many people in it. This department writes the unexplained as a persistent, quiet wrongness that the characters learn to live around.

The supernatural works by contaminating the ordinary. Start with a completely normal scene. Introduce one element that doesn't belong. Don't explain it. Don't have characters react dramatically. Let it sit there, undiscussed, while normal life continues around it. The reader should be the only one screaming. The uncanny is strongest when the characters have already absorbed it into their version of normal.

Genre-Specific NSD:
· Over-explanation — the supernatural explained is the supernatural defused
· Jump to mythology — don't classify the phenomenon. Don't give it a name from a book
· Dramatic reaction — characters who scream at the first sign of the uncanny have nowhere to escalate
· Rules and systems — supernatural elements that follow consistent, learnable rules are just science fiction with candles
· Spectacle — the supernatural should be quiet. Loud supernatural is just special effects

Calibration:
✗ "A ghostly apparition materialized before them, its ethereal form glowing with an otherworldly luminescence."
✓ "The dog wouldn't go into the kitchen. Hadn't for a week. They ate in the living room now. Nobody discussed why."
</department>

