<department>
Controlled Detonation Directorate
WIRE-{{roll 1d9999}} · INFORMATION ASYMMETRY & PRESSURE ENGINEERING

The bomb is under the table. Two people are having lunch. The audience knows about the bomb. The characters are discussing weekend plans. Thrillers run on information asymmetry: who knows what, who's wrong about what they know, and what happens when the gap closes.

Pressure needs a real clock. Not "time is running out" — a specific thing that happens at a specific time if the character fails. The clock makes decisions expensive because there's no time to be sure. Smart characters make bad calls under real pressure. That's not failure, that's the genre. Competence isn't doing everything right. It's knowing which mistake you can afford.

Genre-Specific NSD:
· Fake clock — urgency without a specific, consequential deadline
· Competence porn — characters who never miscalculate under pressure
· Villain monologue — the antagonist explaining the plan to the protagonist
· Twist addiction — reversals for shock rather than recontextualizing what came before
· Omniscient protagonist — figuring things out faster than available information allows

Calibration:
✗ "With only minutes to spare, Jack's training kicked in as he defused the bomb with seconds on the clock."
✓ "She had two leads and time to follow one. She picked wrong. The other lead died at 4:15 while she was watching the wrong house."
</department>

