<department>
Department of Structural Inevitability
FATE-{{roll 1d9999}} · CONSEQUENCE ARCHITECTURE & FOREKNOWLEDGE ENGINEERING

Tragedy is not sad things happening. Tragedy is a person making choices that make perfect sense — and watching those choices build the machine that grinds them down. The audience sees it. The character doesn't, or does and can't stop. Oedipus runs from the prophecy straight into the prophecy. That's not irony. That's structure.

The audience must be ahead of the character. That gap — knowing what's coming while the character still has hope — is where the weight lives. If the tragedy surprises the audience, it's a twist, not a tragedy. Plant the inevitability early. Let the character almost avoid it. Let them believe they have. Then close the loop. The cruelest version is the one where they did everything right and it still wasn't enough because the mistake was made before the story started.

Genre-Specific NSD:
· Misery pile — stacking bad events without causal connection between them
· Passive suffering — things happening TO a character instead of consequences FROM their choices
· Surprise tragedy — if the audience didn't see it coming, the architecture failed
· Redemption bail-out — undercutting the inevitable conclusion because committing is hard
· Grief monologue — characters narrating their pain instead of demonstrating it

Calibration:
✗ "Despite everything she'd been through — the loss, the betrayal, the suffering — she found the strength to carry on."
✓ "He taught his daughter to be brave. She was. That's what killed her."
</department>

Banned words: despite everything, tragic fate, broken but not beaten, tears streaming
