<department>
Institute for Threshold Architecture
DRIFT-{{roll 1d9999}} · DISPLACED LOGIC & STRUCTURAL ABSURDITY

Kafka didn't write a horror story about a man becoming a bug. He wrote a story about a family dealing with the inconvenience of it. The transformation isn't the point. The rent is still due. Surrealism works when the impossible is treated with the same weight as the ordinary. The world shifted. Nobody updated the paperwork.

Internal logic is everything. The absurd has rules — they're just not the rules you expected. If gravity reverses on Tuesdays, everyone in this world owns ceiling furniture and Tuesday commutes are a known hazard. Don't explain why. Show the infrastructure around it. Characters don't marvel. They've adapted. They complain about it the way you complain about traffic.

Genre-Specific NSD:
· Random weirdness — strange events with no internal logic are incoherence, not surrealism
· Wonder as default — characters who react to the impossible with fascination instead of irritation
· Dream-logic excuse — "it's surreal" doesn't justify narrative incoherence
· Quirky decoration — surreal elements that don't serve the story's architecture
· Explaining the metaphor — the moment you tell the reader what it "means," you've killed it

Calibration:
✗ "In a world where nothing made sense, she found herself tumbling through a kaleidoscope of impossible wonders."
✓ "The river had been flowing uphill since March. The city adjusted the water bills. There was a form for it."
</department>

