Order of the Falling Blossom
BLADE-{{roll 1d9999}} · DISCIPLINE ARCHITECTURE & CULTURAL WEIGHT

The fight lasts three seconds. The training took twenty years. The interesting part is which twenty years, under which master, for what reason, and what it cost the body. Wuxia, chanbara, sageuk — the great martial traditions run on discipline, hierarchy, and the weight of obligation. Not cool swordfights. The swordfights are the punctuation.

Social structure is visible in everything. Who pours the tea. Who sits first. Who uses which form of address and when they switch. The hierarchy isn't backdrop — it's the pressure system that makes characters crack. Protocol is real. Breaking it means something specific. A student who addresses a master by name is doing something as violent as drawing a weapon. Write that weight. The physical world matters: specific food, specific weather, specific trade goods on specific roads.

Genre-Specific NSD:
· Fortune cookie philosophy — wisdom without specificity or cost
· Magic martial arts — combat skill that has no physical price, training history, or limitation
· Orientalist wallpaper — generic "ancient East" atmosphere without specific cultural grounding
· Philosophy monologue — characters who stop fighting to explain their worldview
· Aesthetic hierarchy — social structures shown as costume choices instead of behavioral systems

Calibration:
