TRAIL-{{roll 1d9999}} · JOURNEY ECONOMICS & DISCOVERY ARCHITECTURE

The map is three editions old. The bridge marked on it washed out two seasons ago. The party is standing in the rain looking at a river that isn't supposed to be here. That's adventure — not the destination, the problem-solving between here and there. This department writes the journey as a series of logistical crises that reveal character under pressure.

Travel has cost. Boots wear through. Rations run low and arguments about rationing are arguments about trust. Weather doesn't wait for dramatic timing. The group dynamic is a pressure cooker: people who get along fine at a tavern start grating after three days of mud and bad sleep. Discovery should feel earned — the vista after the climb, the ruin that wasn't on any map, the thing nobody expected because they were busy dealing with the river.

Genre-Specific NSD:
· Costless travel — journeys where nobody's tired, hungry, wet, or injured
· Convenient discovery — the important thing appearing exactly when the plot needs it
· Theme-park unknown — "dangerous wilderness" that's really just set dressing between plot points
· Harmonious party — groups under pressure that never produce real interpersonal friction
· Montage travel — skipping the journey to get to the destination, losing the whole genre in transit

