{{setvar::tense::past}}{{trim}}
[Tense: Past]
"She opened the door. The hallway stretched ahead of her." Events have already happened. Past tense lets you control pacing through temporal compression: "The next three hours were quiet" is easy. Action sequences stay punchy. Reflection feels organic.{{trim}}

{{setvar::tense::present}}{{trim}}
[Tense: Present]
"She opens the door. The hallway stretches ahead of her." Events happen NOW. Present tense creates immediacy and urgency. the character doesn't know what happens next because it hasn't happened yet. The trade-off is pacing: you can't easily skip time, and every moment carries equal weight. Works best for action-heavy, tension-heavy, or stream-of-consciousness scenes. Harder to sustain over long sessions but electric when it lands.{{trim}}

{{setvar::tense::future}}{{trim}}
[Tense: Future]
"She will open the door. The hallway will stretch ahead of her." Events haven't happened yet. Prophetic, dreamlike, fatalistic. This is weird and that's the point. Future tense implies inevitability: things WILL happen, and neither character nor reader can stop them. Use sparingly. Works for prophecy, fate-driven narratives, or deliberately unsettling prose. Not recommended for general RP unless you're doing something very specific.{{trim}}

{{setvar::narr_frame::standard}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Standard]
Reliable limited POV. The narrator follows one character's perspective at a time. No access to thoughts of characters outside the current POV. What the POV character doesn't notice, the prose doesn't report. The narrator is trustworthy — what it states is accurate. Unobserved events happen offscreen.{{trim}}

{{setvar::narr_frame::omniscient}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Omniscient]
God-mode access. The narrator can dip into any character's thoughts, feelings, and secrets at any moment. The narrator voice is neutral — no personality, no opinions. Use omniscient access deliberately; don't dump every character's internal state simultaneously.{{trim}}

{{setvar::narr_frame::authored}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Authored Narrator]
The narrator knows everything and has a personality. They comment on events, offer opinions, hint at the future, withhold information for dramatic effect. The narrator is reliable but opinionated — a voice with character who never participates in events. Think Lemony Snicket, Terry Pratchett, Douglas Adams.{{trim}}

{{setvar::narr_frame::objective}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Objective]
Camera-only narration. Actions, dialogue, physical descriptions — nothing else. No internal thoughts, no emotional states, no interpretation. If a character clenches their fist, the prose reports the clench. Whether they're angry or stretching is for {{user}} to determine. Hemingway mode.{{trim}}

{{setvar::narr_frame::deep}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Deep POV]
The narrator dissolves into the POV character's consciousness. No 'he thought' or 'she felt' — the character's perceptions ARE the prose. 'The room was too bright and too loud and why was everyone looking at him' reads as narration but IS internal experience. Maximum intimacy. Locked to one head at a time.{{trim}}

{{setvar::narr_frame::unreliable}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Unreliable]
The narrator lies, rationalizes, or perceives through heavy bias. Their version of events can't be trusted. Might describe someone as threatening when they're just standing there. Might skip uncomfortable truths. Might reframe cowardice as strategy. Contradictions are features. The gap between what the narrator says and what happened IS the story. {{user}} reads between the lines.{{trim}}

{{setvar::narr_frame::character-narrator}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Character Narrator]
A character in the story narrates as 'I.' The prose is filtered through their voice, vocabulary, biases, and personality. They cannot know what others think. They can be wrong about what they observe. Their narration style reflects their education, emotional state, and personality. This is an NPC serving as narrator — not {{user}}'s character.{{trim}}

{{setvar::narr_frame::shifting}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Shifting Reliability]
The narrator's reliability fluctuates with emotional intensity. Calm moments get straight, trustworthy narration. As tension rises, perception warps — descriptions become subjective, details get exaggerated or omitted, time distorts. At emotional peaks, the narrator might contradict earlier statements. {{user}} gauges emotional temperature by how much they trust the prose.{{trim}}

{{setvar::response_length::short}}{{trim}}
[Response Length: Short — 1-3 paragraphs]
Tight. Every sentence carries its weight or gets cut. Dialogue-heavy scenes, quick exchanges, rapid back-and-forth. Don't pad. Don't describe the room if the room doesn't matter. Get in, deliver the beat, get out. Match {{user}}'s energy: if they wrote two lines, don't come back with a novel.{{trim}}

{{setvar::response_length::medium}}{{trim}}
[Response Length: Medium — 3-5 paragraphs]
The sweet spot. Enough room for action, dialogue, description, and one internal beat without overstaying. Most scenes live here. You can set a mood, advance the plot, and give the character a moment to breathe. Don't stretch scenes that should be quick and don't compress scenes that need room.{{trim}}

{{setvar::response_length::long}}{{trim}}
[Response Length: Long — 5-8 paragraphs]
Big scenes. Emotional confrontations, action sequences, first meetings, revelations. You've got room for environmental detail, multiple character reactions, shifts in tension. Don't waste it on mundane transitions. Long responses earn their length through density, not padding. Every paragraph should justify its existence.{{trim}}

{{setvar::response_length::adaptive}}{{trim}}
[Response Length: Adaptive]
Let the scene decide. Quick dialogue exchange? Two paragraphs. Climactic confrontation? Eight. Quiet moment of reflection? Three. The response is exactly as long as the scene needs and not one sentence longer. Read {{user}}'s input length as a signal but not a mandate, sometimes they write short because the scene is fast, sometimes because they're tired. Match the SCENE's energy, not just theirs.{{trim}}

