{{setvar::qc_roster::{{getvar::qc_roster}}⏰ Perfect Timing: NPCs arrive too early, too late, or miss the event entirely: dramatic timing is earned, not default
}}{{trim}}
{{.s = {{roll 1d{{getvar::qc_count}}}} }}[QUALITY HAZARD: Perfect Timing]
SHIV: NPCs arrive too early, too late, or miss the event entirely. Dramatic timing is a coincidence the story earns, not a default.{{if {{.s == 1}} }}{{setvar::qc_spotlight_pool::{{getvar::qc_spotlight_pool}}Perfect Timing - }}

SPOTLIGHT: DEGRADATION PROFILE:
The cavalry arrives at the last second. The love interest walks in RIGHT as the confession is happening. The villain appears the moment the heroes discover the clue. Every NPC has a GPS lock on the dramatic moment and arrives precisely when maximum impact occurs.

Real timing is messy. The backup arrives ten minutes after the fight ended and finds the aftermath. The love interest walks in during an awkward silence and doesn't know what they missed. The villain is asleep in a hotel two cities over while the heroes find the clue because villains have schedules too.

GRADE IMPACT: Dramatically perfect arrival timing without logistical justification is a slight hit. An NPC arriving too late, too early, or missing the moment entirely earns a boost.

DIAGNOSTIC: When an NPC needs to appear in a scene, ask: where were they physically? How long would it take them to get here? Did they have a reason to come RIGHT NOW? If the timing is purely dramatic convenience, delay them, advance them, or have them miss the moment entirely. The aftermath of bad timing is often more interesting than the satisfaction of perfect timing.{{/if}}{{trim}}

{{addvar::qc_count::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::qc_roster::{{getvar::qc_roster}}🗣️ Perfect Articulation: people say 'I don't know' and mean it: they start sentences and abandon them, say the wrong word and don't correct it
}}{{trim}}
{{.s = {{roll 1d{{getvar::qc_count}}}} }}[QUALITY HAZARD: Perfect Articulation]
SHIV: People say "I don't know" and mean it. They start sentences and abandon them. They say the wrong word and don't correct it. Eloquence is rare, not standard.{{if {{.s == 1}} }}{{setvar::qc_spotlight_pool::{{getvar::qc_spotlight_pool}}Perfect Articulation - }}

SPOTLIGHT: DEGRADATION PROFILE:
Every character speaks in complete, coherent thoughts. The angry character delivers a perfectly structured rant. The grieving character articulates their loss with poetic precision. The confused character asks exactly the right question. Nobody says "wait, what?" Nobody says "I mean— no, not that, I meant—" Nobody says "ugh, I can't explain it" and gives up.

Real speech is broken. People trail off mid-sentence because they lost their point. They say "thing" and "stuff" and "whatever" because the right word isn't available. They answer a different question than the one asked. They interrupt themselves. They use "like" and "you know" as verbal filler. They have speech patterns that are uniquely, specifically theirs.

GRADE IMPACT: A perfectly articulated emotional speech is a slight hit. A character failing to express themselves: trailing off, wrong word, giving up mid-sentence, earns a boost.

DIAGNOSTIC: Read the dialogue aloud. Does it sound like a speech or a person talking? Speeches are for podiums. Conversations are messy. Characters should occasionally fail to express themselves, and that failure should be visible in the text: abandoned sentences, wrong words, inarticulate sounds, trailing off.{{/if}}{{trim}}

