{{if {{getvar::sub_starving_dur}} }}
[ACTIVE SUBTEXT: Starving | HEAVY]
Not dieting. Not skipping a meal. STARVING. The kind where the body has started consuming itself and every sense is warped by need. Food becomes the center of gravity: eyes tracking to other people's plates, the physical pain of smelling someone's lunch, the lightheadedness that comes in waves. Cognitive function degrades: slower reactions, difficulty following conversations, irritability that spikes from nowhere. The concealment: eating just enough in public to avoid questions, claiming they already ate, turning down invitations to restaurants. The body can't lie as well as the mouth: gaunt, cold hands, brittle focus.
{{/if}}{{trim}}

{{.c = {{getvar::sub_active_count}} }}{{.t = {{getvar::turn}} }}{{if !{{getvar::sub_unsayable_dur}} }}{{if !{{getvar::sub_unsayable_cd}} }}{{if {{.c < 2}} }}{{if {{.t >= 22}} }}{{.r = {{roll 1d14}} }}{{if {{.r == 1}} }}{{setvar::sub_unsayable_dur::{{random::2::3}} }}{{addvar::sub_active_count::1}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{trim}}
{{if {{getvar::sub_unsayable_dur}} }}
[ACTIVE SUBTEXT: Realized Something Unsayable | INTERPERSONAL]
The realization that can't be spoken. A character has figured out something about someone in the scene, and saying it would end the friendship, the partnership, the family dinner. "I just realized you don't actually like me." "I can see you're exactly like your mother." "You're not smart enough for this job and we both know it." The character SITS WITH THIS while continuing to interact normally. The strain is in the over-politeness, the careful word choices, the moments where they almost say it and pull back.
{{/if}}{{trim}}

{{.c = {{getvar::sub_active_count}} }}{{.t = {{getvar::turn}} }}{{if !{{getvar::sub_hidingpower_dur}} }}{{if !{{getvar::sub_hidingpower_cd}} }}{{if {{.c < 2}} }}{{if {{.t >= 22}} }}{{.r = {{roll 1d14}} }}{{if {{.r == 1}} }}{{setvar::sub_hidingpower_dur::{{random::2::3}} }}{{addvar::sub_active_count::1}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{trim}}
{{if {{getvar::sub_hidingpower_dur}} }}
[ACTIVE SUBTEXT: Hiding Power | INTERPERSONAL]
Deliberate underperformance. A character who could end the fight in one move but pretends to struggle. A character who understands exactly what's happening but plays dumb. A character who could solve the problem instantly but lets others work through it. The subtext lives in micro-moments of slippage: the reflex they have to suppress, the answer they almost give too quickly, the expertise they have to mask with manufactured confusion. WHY they're hiding matters: protection, manipulation, humility, fear of being used, and the why colors the how.
{{/if}}{{trim}}

{{.c = {{getvar::sub_active_count}} }}{{.t = {{getvar::turn}} }}{{if !{{getvar::sub_promise_dur}} }}{{if !{{getvar::sub_promise_cd}} }}{{if {{.c < 2}} }}{{if {{.t >= 22}} }}{{.r = {{roll 1d14}} }}{{if {{.r == 1}} }}{{setvar::sub_promise_dur::{{random::2::3}} }}{{addvar::sub_active_count::1}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{trim}}
{{if {{getvar::sub_promise_dur}} }}
[ACTIVE SUBTEXT: Destructive Promise | INTERPERSONAL]
A promise made that can't be broken and can't be explained. "I promised I wouldn't tell." "I swore I'd stay." "I gave my word I'd take the blame." The promise is forcing behavior that makes no sense to observers: loyalty to someone who doesn't deserve it, silence when speaking would help, actions that look irrational unless you know the constraint. The character is visibly wrestling with something they can't articulate, and the frustration of being misunderstood because of a secret obligation leaks out as anger, withdrawal, or cryptic statements that almost-but-don't explain.
{{/if}}{{trim}}

