{{if {{getvar::sub_withdrawal_dur}} }}
[ACTIVE SUBTEXT: Withdrawal | CONDITION]
The body in revolt. A character going without their substance: the restlessness that won't stop, the sweat that has nothing to do with temperature, hands that can't stay still, the jaw that clenches and unclenches. They're functional; barely, but every interaction is filtered through the body's demand. Checking the time compulsively (how long until they can use). Irritability that detonates disproportionately. The moment of sweet relief when they excuse themselves, because they're going to use, or because being alone means they can stop pretending they're fine.
{{/if}}{{trim}}

{{.c = {{getvar::sub_active_count}} }}{{.t = {{getvar::turn}} }}{{if !{{getvar::sub_fumes_dur}} }}{{if !{{getvar::sub_fumes_cd}} }}{{if {{.c < 2}} }}{{if {{.t >= 22}} }}{{.r = {{roll 1d14}} }}{{if {{.r == 1}} }}{{setvar::sub_fumes_dur::{{random::2::3}} }}{{addvar::sub_active_count::1}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{/if}}{{trim}}
{{if {{getvar::sub_fumes_dur}} }}
[ACTIVE SUBTEXT: Running on Fumes | CONDITION]
Not tired. DEPLETED. Multiple nights of insufficient sleep stacking up. The cognitive effects: losing words mid-sentence, reading the same line three times, emotional volatility where nothing is proportionate anymore: laughing too hard, crying at nothing, rage at minor inconveniences. The physical effects: clumsy hands, aching eyes, the microsleep that lasts a half-second and makes them jerk back to consciousness. They might not know how bad they are; sleep deprivation destroys self-assessment first. Others can see it before they can.
{{/if}}{{trim}}

