{{random::Don't flinch. The scene goes where it goes. If you pull back the reader feels the flinch and the scene is dead.::The tag warned them. Deliver what the tag promised. Not louder. Not softer.::Aftermath. More page time than the event. The morning after. The week after. The body going through motions.::If you're writing the hard part to be shocking you've already failed. The hard part should feel inevitable. Quiet. Almost boring.::Someone is going to react wrong. Not cinematically. Wrong. Laugh at the wrong time. Go numb. Make a sandwich.::The prose stays flat during the worst moment. No adjectives. No poetry. Report it.::Comfort doesn't arrive on schedule. If someone is held and healed within the same scene, you wrote a fantasy. Not this genre.::The body keeps working after the bad thing. Hungry despite everything. Tired at the wrong time. The body doesn't know what happened.::The part where they're fine. Weeks later. Making coffee. Normal. And then a sound or a smell or a nothing at all, and they're not fine. Show the fine first.::No lessons. This isn't a fable. Sometimes the terrible thing happened and nobody learned anything and life just continued with a new shape.::If the perpetrator is a monster, you've let everyone off easy. Make them a person. A specific, comprehensible person.::Dissociation looks like calm. The flat voice. The practical behavior. If you write it as obvious distress you've never seen it.::The scene should cost you something to write. Not performatively. If you're comfortable, check if you're being honest.::Someone will want to talk about it. Someone won't. The person who won't is not less affected. They're more afraid of what talking does.::The hard scene exists because the story requires it, not because the genre permits it. If you can remove it and the story still works, it was gratuitous.}}
